{"title":"Grasp Anything: Combining Teacher-Augmented Policy Gradient Learning with Instance Segmentation to Grasp Arbitrary Objects","domain":"ROBOTICS","seeds":[{"problem":"Learning dexterous grasping directly from visual inputs is sample-inefficient, and naïve policy distillation from a privileged teacher fails to adapt when the student's visual observation space changes the feasible optimal behavior (e.g., self-occlusion breaks tracking).","method":"Teacher-Augmented Policy Gradient (TAPG): a two-stage student–teacher framework. First, train a teacher with policy gradients on privileged low-dimensional states (oriented 3D bounding boxes). Then train a visual student on segmented point clouds with a combined objective: standard policy gradient plus a behavior cloning term gated by the teacher’s advantage/value, so the student imitates only when the teacher is estimated better. This permits deviation to handle visual constraints and comes with a performance guarantee under bounded imitation loss. TAPG learns perception-aware strategies and outperforms both visual RL and pure policy distillation, surpassing the teacher after adaptation."},{"problem":"Real-world deployment with promptable segmentation (e.g., SAM) can fail when grasps fully occlude small targets, causing segmentation/tracking loss; training with VFMs in-the-loop is impractical.","method":"Perception-driven reward and sim-to-real pipeline: in simulation, use ground-truth instance masks and add an auxiliary reward that maximizes a target visibility ratio computed by projecting sampled surface points and counting those inside the mask, encouraging occlusion-benign grasps. At deployment, replace simulator masks with outputs from a promptable segmentation model (SAM) and apply hand dynamics calibration; this yields zero-shot transfer and robust promptable grasping, improving real-world success from 25% (policy distillation) to 55% (TAPG) across cluttered scenarios."}]}
